                                         Detail by Subactivity Group: Defense Acquisition Workforce Development Account
                                                                          ($ In Thousands)

I. Description of Operations Financed:
Established under 10 USC 1705 in 2008, the Defense Acquisition Workforce Development Account (DAWDA) ensures the Department of War (DoW) acquisition workforce
has the personnel and skills to: (1) fulfill its mission, (2) oversee contractor performance, and (3) secure best value for public resources.

A skilled acquisition workforce is critical to delivering warfighting capabilities at the speed of relevance and maintaining military readiness. The DoW remains committed to
collaborating with Congress to ensure the workforce is adequately staffed and trained.

The Department of the Air Force (DAF) leverages DAWDA to recruit, train, and retain acquisition personnel, funding initiatives such as:
   • Training and retention incentives for the Warfighting Acquisition Workforce (WAW).
   • Research to improve acquisition policies and practices.
   • Bridge funding for salaries, rewards, and incentives.

DAWDA supports DAF priorities, including enduring education, formal acquisition training, and development in advanced technologies, aligning with the DoW’s Acquisition
Transformation Strategy (Pillar 2: Elevate and Empower the Workforce). Key programs include Acquisition Initial Qualification Training (AIQT) for Space WAW, Education
with Industry (EWI), and mission engineering via digital threads to accelerate kill chains across Space and Air domains. Future initiatives, such as the Defense Civilian
Training Corps (DCTC), are also supported.

DAWDA remains essential for enabling the DAF to execute the Office of the Under Secretary of War for Acquisition and Sustainment (OSW(A&S)) Acquisition
Transformation Strategy in current and future fiscal years.


II. Force Structure Summary:
Defense Acquisition Workforce Development Account (DAWDA) funding benefits and supports the nearly 47,000 military and civilian acquisition personnel across the
Department of the Air Force (DAF) spanning nine Air Force Major Commands (MAJCOMs) and three Space Force Field Commands (FLDCOMs). In addition to supporting
the DAF structure, DAWDA funding is provided to support military and civilian acquisition personnel assigned to several unified joint-service Combatant Commands
including the U.S. Special Operations Command (USSOCOM), the U.S. Transportation Command (USTRANSCOM), and the U.S. Space Command (USSPACECOM).

The DAF uses DAWDA to support three main categories of initiatives:

Education/Training and Development:

The DAF leverages approximately 68% of its annual DAWDA funding on Education/Training and Development for its Acquisition Workforce.

The DAF funds the development and delivery of formal acquisition training courses and workshops by the Air Force Institute of Technology (AFIT) School of Systems and
Logistics, such as the kinesthetic, competency focused Fundamentals of Acquisition management (FAM 104) course; as well as the AFIT Cyberspace Technical Center of
Excellence (CyTCoE) to enable Artificial Intelligence (AI) capabilities and competencies within the WAW overall. Leadership development, consistent upskilling, and a



