concerted focus on revolutionizing competency-based training for the Warfighting Acquisition Workforce (WAW) are key components to ensure the Department of the Air
Force (DAF)’s acquisition cadre is well suited to not only address today’s programmatic issues as they interact with industry counterparts, but to think more strategically
and be better suited to address future challenges.

The DAF Acquisition Civilian Tuition Assistance (TA) program and the DAF Advanced Academic Certificate/Degree program benefit the acquisition workforce by increasing
education levels and providing another quality recruiting and/or retention incentive tool making the Air Force/Space Force a more attractive/competitive employer to the
available talent pool.

Because of increased need to leverage the Defense Acquisition Workforce Development Account (DAWDA) for emerging needs such as Office of the Under Secretary of
War for Acquisition & Sustainment OSW(A&S) Acquisition Transformation Strategy, the DAF expects to see new Education/Training and Development emerge as a direct
result, including creating new training opportunities that support the Warfighting Acquisition University (WAU) priorities, Bird of Prey and digital initiatives, and unique DAF-
centric training follow-on or complimentary courses.

Analytics and Management Support:

The DAF leverages approximately 2% of its annual DAWDA funding on Analytics and Management Support of the DAWDA program in support of its Acquisition
Workforce. The DAF leverages this funding primarily in direct support of Acquisition Workforce Reform, to enhance the ability of the acquisition workforce to take
advantage of the most modern, cutting-edge tools that are available, including support for Digital Engineering, Cyber, Software Acquisition efforts, Large Language
Modeling (LLM), Artificial Intelligence, and Adaptive Acquisition Framework (AAF).

Recruiting, Retention, and Recognition:

The DAF leverages approximately 30% of its annual DAWDA funding om Recruiting, Retention, and Recognition of its Acquisition Workforce.

The ability to offer hiring incentives (recruitment bonus and/or student loan repayment and tuition assistance) is a decisive factor for DAF hiring, with incentives used to
attract high-quality candidates to high-demand, critical skills in areas such as aeronautical engineering, aerospace engineering, electronics engineering, software
engineering, computer science, cyber, digital, logistics, finance, cost estimating and business. Hiring incentives enable leveling of the playing field when the DAF is
competing with entry-level industry salaries which are, on average, 30% higher than what the DAF can offer.

The DAF's central recruiting team continues to utilize DAWDA funding for recruiting and outreach, including professional LinkedIn licenses, advertising through various
venues, expanded outreach equipment, and the development of more secure and innovative recruiting tools.

OSW(A&S) Acquisition Transformation Strategy will require expanded DAWDA funding dedicated to both recruiting and retention efforts in support of the strategy.
Additional focus on and leveraging of recruiting and retention incentives will be needed to expand our current effort to provide incentives to attract top talent from industry
and to keep our best leaders in the job longer to deliver the best acquisition results.




