                                            OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE, MARINE CORPS RESERVE
                                                               ($ in Millions)

                                             Operations and Maintenance, Marine Corps Reserve (OMMCR)
                  FY 2025              Price               Program             FY 2026            Price           Program            FY 2027
                   Actuals            Growth               Growth              Enacted           Growth           Growth             Estimate
                    330.6              12.4                 -23.1               319.9              6.5              78.3              404.6

The Operation and Maintenance, Marine Corps Reserve (OMMCR) appropriation finances the day-to-day costs of operating the Marine Corps Forces Reserve
(MARFORRES), its functional activities and facilities. The Reserve Component is trained, organized, and equipped in the same manner as the active force and
provides augmentation, reinforcement, and relief to the active component to both mitigate risk and maximize opportunities; and is fundamental to the Marine
Corps’ Total Force concept. The FY 2027 budget request sustains a force of 32,301 Reserve Marines assigned to units across the country. Like the active
component, the Marine Forces Reserve consists of the Marine Forces Reserve headquarters and its subordinate Marine Division, Marine Aircraft Wing, and
Marine Logistics Group, all of which are headquartered in New Orleans, Louisiana. The Reserve component is unique in that the subordinate regiments/groups,
battalions/squadrons, and companies/detachments are located at 158 reserve training centers and sites across the United States.

The FY 2027 estimate of $404.6 million includes a price increase of $6.5 million and a program increase of $78.3 million. Appropriation funds facility
sustainment at 70 percent of the OSD model reflecting the continuation of the Facilities Investment Optimization strategy, the Marine Corps’ initiative for a
holistic Facilities, Sustainment, Restoration and Modernization (FSRM) model; and supports ground depot maintenance active and reserve at 100 percent of the
total force requirement.
